    {
      "title": "Introduction to إنَّ and Its Sisters",
      "titleArabic": "إنَّ وأخواتها",
      "content": [
        "Arabic sentences are of two types: nominal (جملة اسمية) starting with a noun, and verbal (جملة فعلية) starting with a verb.",
        "The particle إنَّ is used for emphasis and changes the case of the subject (mubtada') to accusative (منصوب). The subject after إنَّ is called اسم إنّ."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "إنَّ emphasizes the statement - 'indeed' or 'surely'",
        "The noun after إنَّ takes fathah (accusative case)",
        "The predicate (خبر إنّ) remains in the nominative case (مرفوع)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "إِنَّ الطَّالِبَ مُجْتَهِدٌ", "english": "Indeed, the student is diligent" },
        { "arabic": "إِنَّ الْكِتَابَ جَدِيدٌ", "english": "Indeed, the book is new" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Arabic Sentence Types",
      "titleArabic": "أنواع الجمل",
      "content": [
        "Review of nominal and verbal sentences from Book 1. Nominal sentences begin with a noun (subject/mubtada') and verbal sentences begin with a verb."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Nominal sentence: الطَّالِبُ مُجْتَهِدٌ (The student is diligent)",
        "Verbal sentence: ذَهَبَ الطَّالِبُ (The student went)",
        "Both types are fundamental to Arabic grammar"
      ]
    }
  ],
